WEBVTT

00:00.514 --> 00:08.925
As we move from gathering to listening, our scripture reading today is from the book of Colossians chapter 1, verses 15 to 20.

00:10.587 --> 00:15.994
The sun is the image of the invisible God, the firstborn overall creation.

00:17.055 --> 00:28.690
For in him all things were created, things in heaven and on earth, visible and invisible, whether thrones or powers or rulers or authorities.

00:29.186 --> 00:32.910
All things have been created through him and for him.

00:34.291 --> 00:35.793
He is before all things.

00:36.433 --> 00:38.896
And in him, all things hold together.

00:38.936 --> 00:42.340
And he is the head of the body, the church.

00:43.361 --> 00:51.349
He is the beginning and the firstborn from among the dead so that in everything he might have the supremacy.

00:52.610 --> 00:56.434
For God was pleased to have all his fullness dwell in him.

00:57.154 --> 01:08.829
and through him to reconcile himself to all things, whether things on earth or things in heaven by making peace through his blood shed on the cross.

01:10.051 --> 01:11.413
This is the word of the Lord.

01:12.274 --> 01:13.215
Thanks be to God.

01:18.122 --> 01:18.863
Thank you, Masha.

01:20.104 --> 01:21.426
Hey, kids.

01:23.650 --> 01:25.373
Good to see you all today.

01:25.413 --> 01:28.337
My name's Pete and really glad that you're with us.

01:29.099 --> 01:38.834
If you happen to see my wife Jen today, you'll want to wish her a happy anniversary and congratulate her on staying married to me for 19 years.

01:40.156 --> 01:48.609
So yesterday we celebrated by climbing up Broken Top, which it's winter up there.

01:48.950 --> 01:51.634
I don't recommend it.

01:52.258 --> 01:54.821
We actually got our Christmas tree, because it might as well.

01:55.181 --> 01:57.444
But we had a great time.

01:58.745 --> 02:02.990
Not many girls dream of marrying a pastor, and Jen is no different.

02:06.434 --> 02:08.336
But she just couldn't resist.

02:08.356 --> 02:17.106
And this morning, we are entering into what we're calling the season of harvest.

02:17.126 --> 02:20.530
And this will take us right up until Advent in December.

02:20.674 --> 02:35.346
And during these 10 weeks, as we often do during the fall, we're going to be in a vision series where we're trying to clarify and refocus around the unique calling that God has given us as a church.

02:35.426 --> 02:49.305
And so if you were here a year ago, you may remember our vision series was the work of the people where we walked through the various elements of our Sunday service and tried to understand why we do things the way we do them here on Sundays.

02:49.625 --> 02:56.574
This year, our series is the whole gospel, both and faith in an either or world.

02:56.654 --> 02:59.979
And I can't tell you how excited I am to do this together.

03:00.019 --> 03:05.426
This series has been on the calendar for over a year, but no exaggeration.

03:05.602 --> 03:08.326
It has been 20 years in the making.

03:09.267 --> 03:19.901
I have been thinking about this subject since 2004, when I was a 24-year-old college pastor at a rural mega church in the valley.

03:20.722 --> 03:29.714
And I can't wait to dive in and see how God might use this series to form our hearts and minds into Christ in new and lasting ways.

03:30.690 --> 03:40.421
But before we get to that, I want to take a minute and give you an update on our plans with our building and property here at Sixth and Clay.

03:41.683 --> 03:58.482
A couple months ago, if you remember, we announced that after several years of praying and trying to figure out whether this place was going to be our starter home or our forever home, God has clearly made the way for us.

03:58.626 --> 04:03.113
to start putting down roots and make this our forever home.

04:03.854 --> 04:08.000
And we shared with you in July that that's kind of the plan.

04:08.500 --> 04:15.651
What we also shared is that we have no idea exactly what that's gonna look like or how we're gonna do it.

04:15.851 --> 04:19.496
Or in other words, we have no plans and we have no money.

04:21.099 --> 04:26.066
So whatever we do, we're going to do together as a congregation.

04:26.338 --> 04:47.964
Well, the update is for the last couple months we've been working behind the scenes to find the right partner That would be somebody from the world of building and development and architecture who could kind of serve as a consultant and as a guide through this process and I'm excited to share this morning that we found our guy Starting this week.

04:47.984 --> 04:56.274
We're gonna be working with a local architect by the name of Alex Collins and his firm blue 40 and

04:56.418 --> 05:03.342
We met Alex through Justin Nelson, who's a high-end furniture designer here in our congregation.

05:03.382 --> 05:06.994
The two of them have collaborated on a bunch of really cool projects.

05:07.074 --> 05:19.071
And as I've gotten to know Alex over the last few months and see the kind of work that he does, I just feel like he is a really great fit for where we're at and what we're trying to do.

05:19.211 --> 05:20.232
So he's a local guy.

05:20.292 --> 05:21.514
He's based here in Bend.

05:21.954 --> 05:24.678
He went to architecture school at the University of Oregon.

05:24.778 --> 05:27.442
But other than that, I like him.

05:29.026 --> 05:32.911
And whether you know it or not, you may have seen some of his work around town.

05:32.991 --> 05:39.218
He did the design for the hook and plow, the brand new restaurant in the Hickson building, over on Century.

05:39.639 --> 05:51.954
And prior to that, before going out on his own, he was the lead architect on Caldera High School, which, if you've been inside Caldera, it is such a beautiful and smart building.

05:52.130 --> 06:08.997
And you see Alex's passion for designs that gather communities in spaces that integrate the indoors and the outdoors, utilizing the best building practices and materials when it comes to stewarding God's creation.

06:09.097 --> 06:11.702
And so I am so excited to work with him.

06:12.603 --> 06:13.324
So here's the plan.

06:13.525 --> 06:19.314
This fall, over the next couple months, we're gonna start dreaming together as a church.

06:19.426 --> 06:28.220
Alex is going to kind of help us get organized and we're going to create some opportunities for you to get involved in this process.

06:28.681 --> 06:34.991
We really do want to do this together and so we're going to create some surveys and some focus groups.

06:35.031 --> 06:43.986
We're going to have some family meetings where we can pray and discuss and discern together and try to figure out how God might be leading us forward.

06:44.482 --> 06:48.826
And so we are excited to do this together as a community.

06:49.487 --> 07:01.278
In the meantime, let me remind you quickly of some of the prompts that we're using to sort of shape our prayers when it comes to how we would steward this building and property.

07:01.318 --> 07:02.640
Again, we don't have plans.

07:02.720 --> 07:05.603
We don't know exactly what it's going to look like.

07:06.183 --> 07:13.170
But here's what we see when we dream about what this place could be, six sentences.

07:13.698 --> 07:23.488
We see a place of worship where Christ is proclaimed by generations to come, and His grace is received through word and water, bread and wine.

07:24.429 --> 07:32.317
We see a place of peace for our neighborhood, deeply embedded in our local community, serving as a hub of blessing to our city.

07:33.378 --> 07:40.946
We see a place of justice for the poor, where orphans and widows, migrants, and refugees are welcomed and served in Jesus' name.

07:41.730 --> 07:50.762
We see a place of community where people of all ages, classes, and colors are formed into a vibrant and eclectic expression of the family of God.

07:51.483 --> 08:01.457
We see a place of beauty where the image of our creator is celebrated through creative goodness, artistic excellence, and awe-inspiring architecture.

08:02.178 --> 08:05.202
And we see a place of garden-like flourishing.

08:05.474 --> 08:11.605
for all of creation, where plants and animals, earth and environment are cultivated and cared for.

08:12.246 --> 08:20.902
So these six words, worship, peace, justice, community, beauty and flourishing, we want these to shape our prayers and our vision together.

08:21.022 --> 08:24.087
So again, here's what I want from you.

08:24.107 --> 08:27.794
First of all, I want you to pray, but for real.

08:28.034 --> 08:28.415
Right?

08:28.435 --> 08:31.540
Not just say you will because that's what we do, but actually pray.

08:31.580 --> 08:44.242
Whenever you think of our church over the next several weeks, just quickly ask God for his heart and his mind and his leading.

08:44.354 --> 08:46.777
Number two, I want you to participate in the process.

08:47.257 --> 08:59.391
Whether you've been part of Antioch from the very beginning or you're just new here, we want to invite the whole community when it comes to submitting ideas and being part of the conversations that we're gonna have.

09:00.092 --> 09:02.495
And number three, I want you to plan on giving.

09:03.816 --> 09:07.560
Whatever we do, we're gonna do together and it's gonna take all of us.

09:07.801 --> 09:12.466
So we have a building fund that's open and if you're really itching to give to that now, you can.

09:12.610 --> 09:15.353
But I don't really want you to give just yet.

09:16.355 --> 09:20.179
I don't want you to just drop 50 bucks in and feel like you did your part.

09:21.381 --> 09:26.547
I want you to start thinking about and planning for how you're going to give the biggest gift that you've ever given.

09:27.428 --> 09:29.871
Because that's what it's going to take for us to do this together.

09:30.292 --> 09:31.453
So, sound good?

09:32.234 --> 09:33.996
All right, that's the building update.

09:34.657 --> 09:35.918
Let's get into the whole gospel.

09:37.100 --> 09:42.226
The passage that Marsha read for us from Colossians 1 has served as

09:42.306 --> 09:46.071
really a grounding text for our church over the last several years.

09:46.952 --> 09:49.776
Our vision statement is the reconciliation of all things.

09:49.936 --> 09:53.341
And this passage is where that phrase comes from.

09:53.481 --> 09:58.548
Hopefully, if you've been around here for a while, this is a passage you've become pretty familiar with.

09:59.028 --> 10:12.146
Specifically, verses 19 and 20, which read, for God was pleased to have all his fullness dwell in Christ and through him to reconcile to himself all things.

10:12.258 --> 10:19.025
whether things on earth or things in heaven by making peace through his blood shed on the cross.

10:23.409 --> 10:40.466
We've come back to this passage time and time again over the last few years and we'll keep coming back to it because not only does it contain the vision statement for our church, but it also contains a beautiful and compelling summary of the Christian gospel.

10:41.218 --> 10:50.912
which is that through his life, death, and resurrection, Jesus has saved us and he's saving the world.

10:51.974 --> 11:05.854
He's unleashed the reconciling power of God into all of creation so that everything that's been torn apart by sin and infected with death is now being mended back together and healed by the love of God.

11:06.856 --> 11:10.962
As it's been said, the birth, death, and resurrection of Jesus means that one day

11:11.202 --> 11:13.185
everything sad will come untrue.

11:14.386 --> 11:19.874
Because of who Jesus is and what he's done, God is making all things new, including you and I.

11:20.615 --> 11:37.237
And so this is what Paul is talking about when he summarizes the gospel with this phrase, the reconciliation of all things, the holistic repair of severed relationships with God, with each other, with ourselves, and the rest of creation.

11:38.259 --> 11:40.722
Now, for many of us, this is a much

11:40.866 --> 11:45.571
bigger view of the gospel than we thought.

11:46.472 --> 12:00.226
If we came to faith in the white American evangelical church, then we're probably used to the idea that the gospel was how we could personally be saved and made right with God.

12:00.767 --> 12:07.954
But we may not have ever heard the idea that the gospel is also how God is saving and remaking the world.

12:08.802 --> 12:17.158
And this is why Paul goes on and on about how Christ's death on the cross is about reconciling all things.

12:17.940 --> 12:23.250
In these five verses, he uses the words all things or everything six times.

12:23.714 --> 12:25.896
In Christ, all things were created.

12:25.996 --> 12:27.518
He is before all things.

12:27.638 --> 12:29.420
He holds all things together.

12:29.780 --> 12:35.946
He has supremacy over all things, and in Him, all things are being reconciled.

12:36.126 --> 12:38.969
I don't know if he could be any more clear.

12:39.629 --> 12:44.434
So, for the more quantitatively minded among us, we like to lay it out as a pie chart.

12:44.454 --> 12:47.797
How many things does Paul say God is reconciling?

12:47.837 --> 12:49.799
All things.

12:51.020 --> 12:52.722
That is the gospel.

12:54.338 --> 13:03.467
Which sounds great, but if you're anything like me, then that raises all kinds of questions, right?

13:03.847 --> 13:06.169
Like what does that actually mean?

13:07.050 --> 13:17.019
And if that's actually true, then how would that change the way I think about God and myself and the world and even life itself?

13:17.760 --> 13:24.306
How can I reconcile the gospel that I first believed with this bigger

13:24.546 --> 13:26.950
more expansive vision of the gospel.

13:28.412 --> 13:32.939
I want to start by introducing you to a new shape.

13:35.263 --> 13:50.366
Shape's one of the first things we learned as little kids, squares and circles and triangles, but unless you've been around Antioch for a while or recently attended a new to Antioch dinner, I'm guessing you've never learned what this shape is called.

13:51.769 --> 13:52.690
It looks like

13:52.770 --> 13:57.256
football or a lemon, but it's actually called a mandorla.

13:58.998 --> 14:02.263
A mandorla, which is Italian for almond.

14:02.964 --> 14:04.786
So you can remember it that way.

14:05.767 --> 14:08.631
Here's what I love about the mandorla.

14:09.352 --> 14:16.522
It's a shape that's created in a vent diagram when two circles overlap.

14:17.663 --> 14:22.610
Or in other words, it's the new reality that emerges

14:23.138 --> 14:27.083
when two things that were separated come together.

14:29.286 --> 14:36.035
Which is why, for thousands of years now, Christians have embraced the mandorla as a symbol for our faith.

14:37.256 --> 14:46.789
Because as followers of Jesus, we hold to a number of beliefs that require us to believe two things are true at the same time, right?

14:47.189 --> 14:50.994
So we worship a God who is both three and one.

14:51.906 --> 14:57.013
We follow a Jesus who is both fully divine and fully human.

14:58.134 --> 15:03.441
We seek a kingdom that is both already here and not yet, okay?

15:03.461 --> 15:11.071
And so throughout the history of the church, Christian artists have actually used the mandorla to kind of capture some of these tensions.

15:11.972 --> 15:19.922
Look at the way Jesus has been depicted throughout ancient Christian art, fully human.

15:20.162 --> 15:27.650
yet fully divine, son of God, yet son of man, creator, yet become part of his creation.

15:28.391 --> 15:31.093
If you try to put Jesus just over here, he doesn't fit.

15:31.514 --> 15:34.257
If you put him over there, that doesn't work either.

15:34.277 --> 15:41.765
The real Jesus lives in the sacred overlap where heaven and earth meet.

15:43.847 --> 15:46.930
And so for me, this shape as strange as that sounds,

15:47.810 --> 15:54.923
captures something about who Jesus is and what his kingdom is all about.

15:54.963 --> 16:06.423
And it's been incredibly helpful and clarifying for me, trying to think about what does it mean to be the people of God living in the unique time and place in which we find ourselves.

16:07.845 --> 16:12.754
Because we also, as followers of Jesus, we live in two places at the same time.

16:13.250 --> 16:17.797
We are citizens of the kingdom of heaven and we are residents of central Oregon.

16:18.598 --> 16:20.581
Both those things are true.

16:21.241 --> 16:24.606
We are sinners and we are saints.

16:25.307 --> 16:32.458
We inhabit this world as visitors from the future, but our faith and identity were formed decisively in the past.

16:34.260 --> 16:35.602
And what that means

16:36.162 --> 16:45.681
is that very often faithful followers of Jesus find themselves not fitting nicely into any of the categories that society would put us in.

16:47.204 --> 16:58.226
We often feel pulled to the right or to the left so to speak towards the past or towards progress, but none of those cultural labels really fit.

16:59.458 --> 17:02.142
So I want to show you a way that I've come to think about this.

17:02.402 --> 17:15.422
And some of you have seen it before, but I hope I think it's super helpful when it comes to understanding not just the cultural moment in which we live, but the unique vision and mission that God has given our church.

17:16.223 --> 17:29.042
And so I'll start by saying you've probably noticed that there are really two major streams within Protestant Christianity in our church that have a whole lot in common, but they also have a lot of differences.

17:29.314 --> 17:33.799
And so you could say that on the left, we have a stream called liberalism.

17:33.919 --> 17:37.063
And by liberalism, I'm not talking about politics.

17:37.083 --> 17:40.787
I'm talking about a biblical and theological lens.

17:40.807 --> 17:43.289
And then on the right, you have fundamentalism.

17:44.451 --> 17:54.642
So I want to just use this chart to show you a few examples of what I'm talking about and how these sort of two sides of Christianity in our country

17:54.722 --> 17:57.585
though they have much in common also differ from each other.

17:58.045 --> 18:05.413
And just caveat, this is a way oversimplification or overgeneralization of some of these dynamics.

18:05.473 --> 18:11.459
Of course, we're talking about a spectrum here, but I still think it's helpful to give us a paradigm to work with.

18:11.919 --> 18:13.981
So let's just run through these quickly.

18:14.082 --> 18:22.450
First, when it comes to their understanding of the Christian gospel, liberalism tends to focus on the gospel of Jesus,

18:22.786 --> 18:26.453
while fundamentalism tends to focus on the gospel about Jesus.

18:27.375 --> 18:41.202
I'm going to spend the entire sermon next week breaking this down in detail, but for now, what I mean is that the gospel of Jesus is the gospel that Jesus himself preached, which is repent for the kingdom of God is at hand.

18:41.730 --> 18:50.568
And the gospel about Jesus is the gospel that Paul and the apostles preached, which is how by grace through faith we can be made right with God.

18:51.049 --> 18:55.698
And so both sides, liberalism and fundamentalism use the word gospel, but

18:56.482 --> 19:00.707
You might notice that the often don't sound like they're talking about the same thing, okay?

19:00.727 --> 19:11.961
Next, when it comes to scripture, liberalism tends to emphasize the human authorship of the Bible while fundamentalism tends to emphasize its divine authority.

19:12.702 --> 19:24.055
When it comes to their view of humanity, liberalism sees humans first as image bearers of God and fundamentalism tends to see humans first as beloved sinners in need of salvation.

19:24.876 --> 19:26.258
When they talk about sin,

19:26.914 --> 19:29.979
And liberals tend to see it as a societal problem.

19:30.420 --> 19:31.642
What's wrong with the world?

19:32.162 --> 19:35.628
And fundamentalists tend to talk about sin as an individual problem.

19:35.788 --> 19:36.629
What's wrong with me?

19:37.691 --> 19:54.578
When it comes to Jesus, and again, this is way oversimplified, but liberalism tends to focus on the life of Christ, his incarnation, his ethics, his teaching, while fundamentalism tends to focus on the death of Christ, his atoning sacrifice for our sins.

19:54.690 --> 20:11.149
Next, liberalism tends to emphasize the humanity of Jesus, the fact that he became one of us and lived among us and suffered with us, while fundamentalism emphasizes the deity of Christ, the fact that he was the morally perfect Son of God.

20:11.969 --> 20:19.538
When it comes to the mission of the church, what we're all about, liberalism prioritizes the pursuit of social justice.

20:19.778 --> 20:28.914
making sure everyone has everything they need, and fundamentalism prioritizes the work of evangelism, making sure everyone gets to hear about Jesus.

20:28.934 --> 20:30.557
So that's the first seven examples.

20:31.379 --> 20:32.340
I've got seven more.

20:32.380 --> 20:33.282
Next slide.

20:36.267 --> 20:40.114
And you have no idea how many I trimmed off of this.

20:40.258 --> 20:42.321
I could go on and on.

20:42.782 --> 20:49.393
The primary concern that liberalism has when it comes to the world, the problem with the world, is that it's full of suffering.

20:49.954 --> 20:53.120
Fundamentalism is more concerned that the world is full of sin.

20:53.921 --> 21:06.482
When it comes to their surrounding culture, liberalism tends to embrace whatever it can within culture, while fundamentalism tends to be a little more skeptical and stands in opposition to culture.

21:06.754 --> 21:14.805
Next, if you are someone who's struggling with sin in a liberal environment, you are likely going to be received with a posture of grace.

21:15.386 --> 21:21.474
While in a fundamentalist environment, you'll most likely hear the truth about what God requires.

21:22.335 --> 21:33.170
When it comes to their priorities in the ministry of the church, liberalism prioritizes meeting people's physical needs, while fundamentalism is more interested in meeting people's spiritual needs.

21:33.602 --> 21:38.569
On the left, holiness looks like doing good, and on the right, it looks like being good.

21:40.071 --> 21:50.246
When they talk about the kingdom of God, liberals tend to talk about it like it's something that's already here, and fundamentalists tend to talk about it like it's something that's still coming.

21:50.827 --> 22:00.882
And finally, if you had to have a patron saint in liberalism, it might be the Reverend Dr. Martin Luther King, or on the right, it might be Reverend Billy Graham.

22:00.962 --> 22:15.283
Dr. King, who gave his life to the black struggle for equality and liberation, and Reverend Graham, who spent his life preaching the gospel to millions of people all around the world.

22:15.723 --> 22:21.331
Like I said, I could go on and on, but I hope you're starting to recognize these two streams.

22:22.873 --> 22:26.378
Technically, they are part of the same family.

22:26.499 --> 22:28.882
We're all Christians.

22:29.090 --> 22:32.763
but oftentimes there's very little family resemblance between the two.

22:33.526 --> 22:40.050
And I wonder if maybe you start to identify some of your own story within this paradigm.

22:40.514 --> 22:48.406
Because I know that for me, the Christianity that I was most familiar with for most of my life really looked like the right side of the chart.

22:48.867 --> 23:01.006
Not that I was in some hardcore fundamentalist environment, but I know that that's the side of things that primarily shaped my faith in the first part of my life.

23:01.046 --> 23:08.498
And I know that's true for a lot of you as well, that you came to Jesus through the door on the right, so to speak.

23:08.834 --> 23:22.015
If you're anything like me at some point, you started to feel like the Christianity you had received was good and true, but maybe not complete.

23:22.856 --> 23:30.248
Like maybe you were still missing something and you started to feel like, man, maybe I've only got half the gospel here.

23:31.069 --> 23:36.978
Maybe the good news of Jesus is actually way bigger and way better than I ever could have imagined.

23:37.250 --> 23:39.874
I know a lot of us, that's been our story.

23:40.575 --> 23:49.589
Now, it's not everybody hears story, maybe you came to Jesus through the door on the left, or maybe you're like, I have no idea what we're talking about, I just love Jesus.

23:50.010 --> 23:53.255
So, that's great, that's fine.

23:55.198 --> 23:59.585
But here's what we're trying to do at Antioch.

23:59.605 --> 24:02.549
We're trying to embrace the whole gospel.

24:03.851 --> 24:05.714
We don't wanna be liberal Christians,

24:06.082 --> 24:07.544
or fundamentalist Christians.

24:08.485 --> 24:16.516
Because we don't think either one of those categories really captures who Jesus is and what his kingdom is all about.

24:18.319 --> 24:20.662
Like wouldn't it be great if we didn't have to choose?

24:22.124 --> 24:27.171
What if we didn't have to settle for just one half of the gospel or the other?

24:28.133 --> 24:34.962
What would it look like to be a church that's actually chasing after the whole gospel?

24:36.418 --> 24:44.870
as in a church that proclaims both the gospel of Jesus and the gospel about Jesus.

24:44.890 --> 24:50.418
A church that recognizes both the human authorship and the divine authority of the Bible.

24:51.440 --> 24:57.248
What if we saw humanity as both image bearers of God and dearly beloved sinners?

24:58.169 --> 25:04.178
What if we cared about both the societal and the individual aspects of sin?

25:04.514 --> 25:11.184
What if we preached both the life and death of Christ, both His humanity and His deity?

25:11.845 --> 25:17.493
What if we gave ourselves both to the work of social justice and the work of evangelism?

25:18.094 --> 25:21.498
What if we cared about sin and suffering?

25:22.260 --> 25:29.390
What if we were to be discerning with culture, learning how to both embrace and oppose when necessary?

25:30.071 --> 25:32.274
What if, like Jesus, we were full

25:32.610 --> 25:34.673
of both grace and truth.

25:35.715 --> 25:41.002
What if we laid down our lives to serve our neighbors' physical and spiritual needs?

25:41.864 --> 25:45.449
What if we were known for both doing good and being good?

25:46.410 --> 25:52.439
What if we believed the good news that the kingdom of God has already come, and yet it is still coming?

25:53.080 --> 25:59.450
And what if we honored the legacies of folks like both Dr. King and Reverend Graham?

26:00.832 --> 26:02.514
Sounds like fun, huh?

26:03.874 --> 26:09.061
Which isn't as crazy as it sounds, you know why?

26:09.121 --> 26:12.125
Because they were friends.

26:14.908 --> 26:26.403
And they had some pretty major differences in their theology and in their approach to ministry, but they both knew that the other one loved Jesus and was doing his part to serve God.

26:28.286 --> 26:31.410
That's a little taste of what we're talking about

26:31.970 --> 26:35.074
when we say we wanna be a church that's about the whole gospel.

26:35.975 --> 26:38.278
And we're gonna talk about this more in the coming weeks.

26:38.298 --> 26:46.229
We're gonna take a few of those elements from the chart and give some significant time to breaking down what that actually looks like.

26:48.371 --> 26:59.666
Because it's important to understand that when we talk about being a both and church in an either or a world, we're not talking about what you might call centrism.

27:00.226 --> 27:07.515
We're not talking about occupying a mushy middle that can't decide what it believes and doesn't want to hurt anybody's feelings.

27:08.356 --> 27:09.578
That's not what this is.

27:09.978 --> 27:17.968
When we talk about pursuing the whole gospel, we're talking about a clear, passionate, radical third way.

27:19.129 --> 27:26.318
In other words, if you know color theory, if you mix orange and blue, you should get a really ugly brown.

27:28.521 --> 27:29.362
But for us,

27:29.506 --> 27:30.888
orange and blue make gold.

27:32.910 --> 27:39.399
So this isn't some mushy, moderate middle because Pete's in Enneagram 9 and can't make up his mind.

27:39.459 --> 27:49.912
This is our way of trying to figure out how to be faithful to a king whose kingdom isn't from this world, but it is for this world.

27:51.554 --> 27:54.738
Because in the end, our hope isn't in a geometric shape.

27:55.458 --> 27:57.321
It's not in a vision statement.

27:57.401 --> 27:58.382
It's not in a chart.

27:58.883 --> 28:02.087
It's not in a slick philosophy of ministry.

28:02.768 --> 28:05.672
Our hope is in Jesus himself.

28:06.974 --> 28:15.025
He is the king who created all things, holds all things together and is making all things new.

28:16.227 --> 28:24.018
And so, Annie, like my invitation to you this morning is would you ask the Holy Spirit to open your eyes

28:24.514 --> 28:38.332
that you might see the glory of the real Jesus and the fullness of his gospel as he reconciles all things to himself, including you and me.

28:39.274 --> 28:40.658
Amen.

